      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Housing Crisis</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Nancy Locker, Citizens' Committee for Children of New York, says housing shortage in New York City is hitting low- and middle-income families hardest, and even least expensive rental housing in city is unaffordable for most poor families (Aug 3 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mayor Favors Plans to Ease Housing Shortage'' (news article, Aug. 3):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mayor Favors Plans to Ease Housing Shortage'' (news article, Aug. 3):</p>
        <p>Since 1993, monthly rents in New York City have increased, hitting low-  and middle-income families the hardest. New Yorkers in 21 of the city's 59 community districts spend more than 30 percent of their annual income on rent. By federal standards, even the least expensive rental housing in New York City is unaffordable for most poor families.</p>
        <p>New housing construction, tax abatements and housing subsidies top the list of ways to help families who want to live, work and raise their children in New York City. But while the city needs to develop a housing plan, it also needs state and federal partners to help pay for it.</p>
        <p>NANCY LOCKER  New York, Aug. 3, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president of the Citizens' Committee for Children of New York.</p>
      </block>
